SIMPLE: detriment
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Detriment
<hw>Det"ri*ment</hw> <pr>(d⟦ecr⟧t"r⟦icr⟧*m⟦eit⟧nt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[L. <ets>detrimentum</ets>, fr. <ets>deterere</ets>,
<ets>detritum</ets>, to rub or wear away; <ets>de</ets> +
<ets>terere</ets> to rub: cf. F. <ets>d⟦eacute⟧triment</ets>. See
<er>Trite</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which injures or causes
damage; mischief; harm; diminution; loss; damage; -- used very
generically; <as>as, <ex>detriments</ex> to property, religion, morals,
etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I can repair⟦br⟧
That <qex>detriment</qex>, if such it be.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A charge made to students and barristers for
incidental repairs of the rooms they occupy.</def>
<mark>[Eng.]</mark></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Injury; loss; damage; disadvantage; prejudice;
hurt; mischief; harm.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Detriment</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Detriment
<hw>Det"ri*ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To do injury
to; to hurt.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Other might be <qex>determined</qex> thereby.</q>
<rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Detrimental</ent>⟦br⟧
